model_sarilumab_only =

# Load original data file
d = import(here("final_analyses", "data", "mortality_data.xlsx"))

# Remove studies that have 0 total events in both treatment arms (3 studies)
d = 
  d %>% 
  filter((control_events + trt_events) != 0)

# Calculate log odds ratio

d_logOR = 
  escalc(
  measure = "OR", # log odds ratio,
  
  # Tocilizumab/Sarilumab
  ai = trt_events,
  n1i = trt_total,
  
  # Control
  ci = control_events,
  n2i = control_total,
  
  data = d
) %>%
  as_tibble() %>% 
  # Dummy approach, tocilizumab = 0, sarilumab = 1
  mutate(treatment = ifelse(treatment == "tocilizumab", 0, 1)) %>% 
  # Calculate standard error
  mutate(sei = sqrt(vi))

In this document, I present our main analyses. Odds ratio lower than 1 means treatment benefit.

The full explanation about these analyses can be found in our preregistered analysis plan: https://osf.io/kvuqr/


What is the effect of sarilumab in reducing mortality?

First, lets estimate the posterior distribution of sarilumabs overall effect using weakly informative priors for \(\mu_{sarilumab}\) and \(\tau\).


\[ \begin{align*} y_i & \sim Normal(\theta_i, \sigma_i^2) \tag{Likelihood}\\ \theta_i & \sim Normal(\mu_{sarilumab}, \tau^2)\\ \\ \mu_{sarilumab} & \sim \operatorname{Normal}(0, 1.5^2) \tag{Priors}\\ \tau & \sim \operatorname{Half-Normal}(0.5) \\ \end{align*} \]

p1 = 
  d_logOR %>%
  filter(treatment == "1") %>% 
  mutate(ub = yi + 1.96*sei,
         lb = yi - 1.96*sei,
         yiOR = exp(yi),
         lbOR = exp(lb),
         ubOR = exp(ub),
         # Reverse order of studies
         study = fct_rev(study)) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = yiOR, xmin = lbOR, xmax = ubOR, y = study)) +
  geom_pointinterval() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1, linetype = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 3, 0.5)) +

Is sarilumab noninferior/equivalent to tocilizumab?

Next, lets estimate the posterior probability of noninferiority and equivalence between sarilumab and tocilizumab. To this end, we fitted a model incorporing data from both drugs. Then, we estimated the posterior distribution of sarilumab and tocilizumab (odds ratio scale). Finally, we compared both posterior distributions by calculating the ratio of odds ratios (sarilumab vs.tocilizumab).

Of note, the estimate posterior distribution of sarilumabs effect is slightly different from the one showed above in Figure 1. A possible explanation for this phenomenon is that now we are fitting one model including both drugs, which yields a more precise posterior distribution for \(\tau\). Because of this, the estimated variance around sarilumabs posterior distribution is smaller, which explains the slightly narrower 95% credible interval ([0.78, 1.37] vs.[0.69 - 1.40]) and lower posterior probability of any benefit (36% vs.42%).



\[\begin{align*} y_i & \sim Normal(\theta_i, \sigma_i^2) \tag{Likelihood}\\ \theta_i & \sim Normal(\mu, \tau^2)\\ \mu &= \beta_0 + \beta_1 x\\ \\ \beta_0 & \sim \operatorname{Normal}(0, 1.5^2) \tag{Priors} \\ \beta_1 & \sim \operatorname{Normal}(0, 1^2) \\ \tau & \sim \operatorname{Half-Normal}(0.5) \\ \end{align*}\]



\[\begin{align*} exp(\beta_1) = \frac {OR_{sarilumab}}{OR_{tocilizumab}} \end{align*}\]

# Sari: 1.06 [0.78, 1.37]
# Toci: 0.84 [0.71, 1.00]   

# ratioOR: 1.27 [0.89, 1.69]

What is the effect of sarilumab using informative priors based on tocilizumab?

Lastly, lets estimate the posterior distribution of sarilumabs effect using informative priors for \(\mu_{sarilumab}\) based on tocilizumab. First, we recalculated the standard errors for each tocilizumab study using the following formula:

\[\begin{equation*} \sigma_{i[W]}^2 = \frac{1}{Wa_i+\frac{1}{2}} + \frac{1}{Wb_i+\frac{1}{2}} + \frac{1}{Wc_i+\frac{1}{2}} + \frac{1}{Wd_i+\frac{1}{2}} \end{equation*}\]

where \(W\) is the weight, ranging from \(0.01\) to \(1\). We then performed separate frequentist random-effect meta-analyses for each set of tocilizumab studies and \(W\) to estimate an overall effect for tocilizumab (\(\mu_{tocilizumab[W]}\)), as further described in the another report in my GitHub and in the analysis plan. Here are the tocilizumabs overall effects for different \(W\):

frequentist_models_prior_mean_sd %>% 
  mutate(ub = mean + 1.96*sd,
         lb = mean - 1.96*sd,
         yiOR = exp(mean),
         lbOR = exp(lb),
         ubOR = exp(ub)) %>% 
  select(weight, yiOR, lbOR, ubOR) %>% 
  
  ggplot() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype = 2) +

Prior distributions based on tocilizumabs studies at different weights. Interval bars depict the mean and 95% confidence interval.



Next, we performed Bayesian random-effect meta-analyses on sarilumab using the estimates depicted above as prior distributions.

\[\begin{align*} y_i & \sim Normal(\theta_i, \sigma_i^2) \\ \theta_i & \sim Normal(\mu_{sarilumab[W]}, \tau^2)\\ \end{align*}\]

Here are the prior distributions, where \(M_{[W]} = mean(\mu_{tocilizumab[W]})\), and \(M_{[W]} = Standard Error(\mu_{tocilizumab[W]})\):

\[\begin{align*} \mu_{sarilumab{[W]}} & \sim \operatorname{Normal}(M_{[W]}, S_{[W]}) \\ \tau & \sim \operatorname{Half-Normal}(0.5) \end{align*}\]

These are our results:

posteriors_sari_with_toci = 
  data.frame(weight = c(0.01, 0.05, seq(from = 0.1, to =  1, by = 0.1)),
                  mean = NA, lb = NA, ub = NA)


for (i in 1:nrow(posteriors_sari_with_toci)) {
  
  posteriors_sari_with_toci[i, c("mean", "lb", "ub")] = 
    
    # models_sarilumab_w contains all twelve models (1 per weight)
    # [[1]] = weight of 0.01, [[2]] = w of 0.05, and so on
    (models_sarilumab_w[[i]] %>%
       # Select posterior distribution of mu_sarilumab
       fixef() %>%
       # Exponentiate to transform into the odds ratio scale
       # and extract mean, Standard Error 95% Crl lower and upper bound
       exp())[1,(c("Estimate", "Q2.5", "Q97.5"))] 
}

# Create data.frame to fill with mean, Standard Error, 95% Crl lower and upper bound below
probabilities_sari_with_toci = 
  data.frame(weight = c(0.01, 0.05, seq(from = 0.1, to =  1, by = 0.1)),
                  p1 = NA, p90 = NA, p85 = NA, p80 = NA, p75 = NA)


for (i in 1:nrow(probabilities_sari_with_toci)) {
  
  probabilities_sari_with_toci[i, c("p1", "p90", "p85", "p80", "p75")] =
    
    # models_sarilumab_w contains all twelve models (1 per weight)
    # [[1]] = weight of 0.01, [[2]] = w of 0.05, and so on
    (models_sarilumab_w[[i]] %>%
        posterior_samples() %>% 
        summarise(p1  = 100*mean(exp(b_Intercept) < 1),
                  p90 = 100*mean(exp(b_Intercept) < 0.95),
                  p85 = 100*mean(exp(b_Intercept) < 0.85),
                  p80 = 100*mean(exp(b_Intercept) < 0.80),
                  p75 = 100*mean(exp(b_Intercept) < 0.75)
                  ))[1,(c("p1", "p90", "p85", "p80", "p75"))] 
       
}
p2 = probabilities_sari_with_toci %>% 
  pivot_longer(p1:p75) %>% 
  mutate(
    name = case_when(
      
    name == "p1" ~ "< 1",
    name == "p90" ~ "< 0.9",
    name == "p85" ~ "< 0.85",
    name == "p80" ~ "< 0.80",
    name == "p75" ~ "< 0.75"),
    
    name = factor(name, levels = c("< 1", "< 0.9", "< 0.85", "< 0.80", "< 0.75"))
    ) %>% 
  filter(name != "< 0.75") %>% 
  rename("Odds Ratio" = name) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = 100*weight, y = value, group = `Odds Ratio`, color = `Odds Ratio`)) +
  geom_segment(aes(x = pull(prob_equivalence), xend = pull(prob_equivalence),
                   y = 0, yend = 100),
               size = 0.2, color = "black", linetype = 2) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  scale_color_manual(values= pnw_palette(name="Bay",n=5)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1, pull(prob_equivalence), seq(20, 100, 20))) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 100, 20)) +
  labs(x = "\nWeight on Tocilizumab (%)",
       y = "Probability of Benefit (%)\n") +

Panel A: Red interval bar depict the mean and 95% credible interval (Crl) of sarilumabs overall effect using weakly informative priors (Figure 1). Black dashed lines represent prior distributions for overall effect based on tocilizumabs data at different weights. Purple dashed areas represent the posterior distribution 95% Crls of sarilumabs overall effect when using tocilizumabs data as the prior distribution at different weights. Black solid line depict the mean of these posterior distributions. Panel B: Based on posterior distributions of sarilumabs effect using tocilizumab as prior, each line represents the posterior probability of benefit for a specific cutoff, such as odds ratio lower than 1, 0.9, 0.85 and 0.80. Vertical blacked dashed line depict 31%, which is the estimated posterior probability of equivalence between sarilumab and tocilizumab (Figure 2).
